[0m[49m[39m  132, 144[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  133, 145[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  134, 146[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  135, 147[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  136, 148[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Hosts the trained CNN model; provides GPU-backed real-time inference endpoint |
[0m[49m[39m  137, 149[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores incoming DICOM files and model artifacts; encrypted with KMS |
[0m[49m[39m  138, 150[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Orchestrates the pipeline: routes studies, triggers preprocessing, calls inference, formats results |
[0m[49m[39m  139, 151[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores inference results, priority scores, and audit trail |
[0m[49m[39m  140, 152[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Manages encryption keys for S3, DynamoDB, and SageMaker volumes |
[0m[49m[39m  141, 153[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Metrics, logs, and alarms for inference latency, error rates, and confidence drift |
[0m[49m[39m  142, 154[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SNS** | Alerts operations team when model drift or errors are detected |
[0m[49m[39m  143, 155[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  144, 156[0m:[39m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[39m  145, 157[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  146, 158[0m:[39m[49m > **Reference implementations:** The following AWS sample repos demonstrate patterns relevant to this recipe:
[0m[49m[39m  147, 159[0m:[39m[49m >
[0m[49m[39m  148, 160[0m:[39m[49m > - [`amazon-sagemaker-medical-imaging`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-sagemaker-medical-imaging): SageMaker-based medical imaging inference pipelines including DICOM handling <!-- TODO: verify this repo still exists -->
[0m[49m[39m  149, 161[0m:[39m[49m > - [`aws-healthimaging-samples`](https://github.com/aws-samples/aws-healthimaging-samples): Working with AWS HealthImaging for DICOM storage and retrieval
[0m[49m[39m  150, 162[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  151, 163[0m:[39m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[39m  152, 164[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  153, 165[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Receive and filter DICOM studies.** When a new imaging study arrives in the S3 landing zone, the system checks whether it's a chest X-ray. Not every study needs triage. We filter using DICOM metadata: modality (CR or DX for computed/digital radiography), body part examined (CHEST), and view position (PA or AP). Non-chest studies are ignored. This filtering prevents wasted inference costs and keeps the model focused on what it was trained for. Skip this step and you'll be running knee X-rays through a chest model, burning GPU time and generating meaningless results.
[0m[49m[39m  154, 166[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  155, 167[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  156, 168[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION route_study(bucket, key):
[0m[49m[39m  157, 169[0m:[39m[49m     // Read DICOM metadata from the file header (not the pixel data, just the tags).
[0m[49m[39m  158, 170[0m:[39m[49m     // DICOM files contain structured metadata describing the study, patient, and acquisition.
[0m[49m[39m  159, 171[0m:[39m[49m     metadata = read DICOM tags from S3 object at bucket/key
[0m[49m[39m  160, 172[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  161, 173[0m:[39m[49m     // Check if this study is a chest X-ray based on standard DICOM tags.
[0m[49m[39m  162, 174[0m:[39m[49m     // Modality "CR" = Computed Radiography, "DX" = Digital Radiography (both are X-ray types).
[0m[49m[39m  163, 175[0m:[39m[49m     // BodyPartExamined tells us what anatomy was imaged.
[0m[49m[39m  164, 176[0m:[39m[49m     IF metadata.Modality in ["CR", "DX"]
[0m[49m[39m  165, 177[0m:[39m[49m        AND metadata.BodyPartExamined == "CHEST":
[0m[49m[39m  166, 178[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  167, 179[0m:[39m[49m         // This is a chest X-ray. Send it to the preprocessing pipeline.
[0m[49m[39m  168, 180[0m:[39m[49m         trigger_preprocessing(bucket, key, metadata)
[0m[49m[39m  169, 181[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  170, 182[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  171, 183[0m:[39m[49m         // Not a chest X-ray. Log it and move on. No inference needed.
[0m[49m[39m  172, 184[0m:[39m[49m         log("Skipping non-chest study: " + key)
[0m[49m[39m  173, 185[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  174, 186[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  175, 187[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Preprocess the DICOM image for model input.** Raw DICOM pixel data is not ready for a neural network. DICOM images can be 12-bit or 16-bit, have varying dimensions, use different photometric interpretations (some are inverted: white = air, black = bone), and may include burned-in annotations or borders. This step extracts the pixel array, normalizes intensity values to the range the model expects, resizes to the model's input dimensions, and handles photometric inversion. The preprocessing must exactly replicate what was done during model training. Even small differences (different resize interpolation, different normalization range) can degrade accuracy significantly. This is one of the most common deployment failures in medical imaging AI.
[0m[49m[39m  176, 188[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  177, 189[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  178, 190[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION preprocess_for_inference(bucket, key):
[0m[49m[39m  179, 191[0m:[39m[49m     // Load the full DICOM file including pixel data.
[0m[49m[39m  180, 192[0m:[39m[49m     dicom_file = load DICOM from S3 at bucket/key
[0m[49m[39m  181, 193[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  182, 194[0m:[39m[49m     // Extract the raw pixel array. This is typically a 2D array of integers.
[0m[49m[39m  183, 195[0m:[39m[49m     // Values might range from 0 to 4095 (12-bit) or 0 to 65535 (16-bit).
[0m[49m[39m  184, 196[0m:[39m[49m     pixel_array = dicom_file.pixel_array
[0m[49m[39m  185, 197[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  186, 198[0m:[39m[49m     // Handle photometric interpretation.
[0m[49m[39m  187, 199[0m:[39m[49m     // "MONOCHROME1" means high values = dark (inverted from what models expect).
[0m[49m[39m  188, 200[0m:[39m[49m     // Most models are trained with "MONOCHROME2" convention (high values = bright).
[0m[49m[39m  189, 201[0m:[39m[49m     IF dicom_file.PhotometricInterpretation == "MONOCHROME1":
[0m[49m[39m  190, 202[0m:[39m[49m         pixel_array = invert(pixel_array)  // flip so high values = bright
[0m[49m[39m  191, 203[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  192, 204[0m:[39m[49m     // Apply windowing if window center/width are specified.
[0m[49m[39m  193, 205[0m:[39m[49m     // Windowing maps the full dynamic range to a clinically relevant subset.
[0m[49m[39m  194, 206[0m:[39m[49m     // This mimics what the radiologist sees on their display.
[0m[49m[39m  195, 207[0m:[39m[49m     IF dicom_file has WindowCenter AND WindowWidth:
[0m[49m[39m  196, 208[0m:[39m[49m         pixel_array = apply_window(pixel_array,
[0m[49m[39m  197, 209[0m:[39m[49m                                    center = dicom_file.WindowCenter,
[0m[49m[39m  198, 210[0m:[39m[49m                                    width  = dicom_file.WindowWidth)
[0m[49m[39m  199, 211[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  200, 212[0m:[39m[49m     // Normalize pixel values to [0, 1] range.
[0m[49m[39m  201, 213[0m:[39m[49m     // Neural networks expect inputs in a consistent, small numeric range.
[0m[49m[39m  202, 214[0m:[39m[49m     pixel_array = normalize_to_0_1(pixel_array)
[0m[49m[39m  203, 215[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  204, 216[0m:[39m[49m     // Resize to model's expected input dimensions (e.g., 224x224 or 512x512).
[0m[49m[39m  205, 217[0m:[39m[49m     // Use the same interpolation method used during training (typically bilinear).
[0m[49m[39m  206, 218[0m:[39m[49m     pixel_array = resize(pixel_array, target_size = MODEL_INPUT_SIZE,
[0m[49m[39m  207, 219[0m:[39m[49m                          interpolation = "bilinear")
[0m[49m[39m  208, 220[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  209, 221[0m:[39m[49m     // Return the preprocessed image ready for inference.
[0m[49m[39m  210, 222[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN pixel_array
[0m[49m[39m  211, 223[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  212, 224[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  213, 225[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Run inference on the triage model.** The preprocessed image is sent to the SageMaker endpoint hosting the trained model. The model returns a probability score for each finding category it was trained to detect. For a triage use case, the critical findings are typically: pneumothorax, large pleural effusion, cardiomegaly, pulmonary edema, and mass/nodule. The inference call should complete in under 5 seconds. If it takes longer, the triage value diminishes (the radiologist might have already opened the study). Monitor latency closely.
[0m[49m[39m  214, 226[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  215, 227[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  216, 228[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION run_inference(preprocessed_image, study_id):
[0m[49m[39m  217, 229[0m:[39m[49m     // Serialize the preprocessed image into the format the endpoint expects.
[0m[49m[39m  218, 230[0m:[39m[49m     // Most SageMaker endpoints accept numpy arrays serialized as bytes or JSON.
[0m[49m[39m  219, 231[0m:[39m[49m     payload = serialize_image(preprocessed_image)
[0m[49m[39m  220, 232[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  221, 233[0m:[39m[49m     // Call the SageMaker real-time inference endpoint.
[0m[49m[39m  222, 234[0m:[39m[49m     // The endpoint name identifies which model version to use.
[0m[49m[39m  223, 235[0m:[39m[49m     // ContentType tells SageMaker how to deserialize the input.
[0m[49m[39m  224, 236[0m:[39m[49m     response = call SageMaker.InvokeEndpoint with:
[0m[49m[39m  225, 237[0m:[39m[49m         EndpointName = "cxr-triage-model-v2"
[0m[49m[39m  226, 238[0m:[39m[49m         ContentType  = "application/x-npy"    // numpy array format
[0m[49m[39m  227, 239[0m:[39m[49m         Body         = payload
[0m[49m[39m  228, 240[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  229, 241[0m:[39m[49m     // Parse the response: a dictionary of finding names to probability scores.
[0m[49m[39m  230, 242[0m:[39m[49m     // Example: {"pneumothorax": 0.92, "pleural_effusion": 0.15, "cardiomegaly": 0.03, ...}
[0m[49m[39m  231, 243[0m:[39m[49m     predictions = deserialize(response.Body)
[0m[49m[39m  232, 244[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  233, 245[0m:[39m[49m     // Log the raw predictions for audit and monitoring.
[0m[49m[39m  234, 246[0m:[39m[49m     log_inference_result(study_id, predictions)
[0m[49m[39m  235, 247[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  236, 248[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN predictions
[0m[49m[39m  237, 249[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  238, 250[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  239, 251[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Calculate priority score and determine triage action.** Raw probability scores need to be converted into a clinical priority decision. This step applies finding-specific thresholds (pneumothorax has a lower threshold than cardiomegaly because it's more time-sensitive) and assigns a composite priority level. The priority levels map to worklist behavior: CRITICAL means interrupt the radiologist now, URGENT means move to top of queue, ROUTINE means normal ordering. The thresholds are the most important tunable parameters in the system. Set them too low and you flood the radiologist with false alarms (alert fatigue kills clinical AI adoption faster than anything). Set them too high and you miss the findings that matter. Calibrate on your institution's data with radiologist input.
[0m[49m[39m  240, 252[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  241, 253[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  242, 254[0m:[39m[49m // Thresholds per finding, calibrated on institutional validation data.
[0m[49m[39m  243, 255[0m:[39m[49m // Lower threshold = more sensitive (fewer misses, more false alarms).
[0m[49m[39m  244, 256[0m:[39m[49m // These values are examples; real thresholds require clinical validation.
[0m[49m[39m  245, 257[0m:[39m[49m FINDING_THRESHOLDS = {
[0m[49m[39m  246, 258[0m:[39m[49m     "pneumothorax":      0.60,   // life-threatening; err on the side of alerting
[0m[49m[39m  247, 259[0m:[39m[49m     "tension_pneumo":    0.50,   // immediately life-threatening; very low threshold
[0m[49m[39m  248, 260[0m:[39m[49m     "large_effusion":    0.70,   // clinically significant but less emergent
[0m[49m[39m  249, 261[0m:[39m[49m     "pulmonary_edema":   0.70,   // urgent but not immediately life-threatening
[0m[49m[39m  250, 262[0m:[39m[49m     "mass_or_nodule":    0.75,   // important but not time-critical in minutes
[0m[49m[39m  251, 263[0m:[39m[49m     "cardiomegaly":      0.80    // relevant but rarely emergent
[0m[49m[39m  252, 264[0m:[39m[49m }
[0m[49m[39m  253, 265[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  254, 266[0m:[39m[49m // Clinical severity weights for composite scoring.
[0m[49m[39m  255, 267[0m:[39m[49m SEVERITY_WEIGHTS = {
[0m[49m[39m  256, 268[0m:[39m[49m     "tension_pneumo":    10,
[0m[49m[39m  257, 269[0m:[39m[49m     "pneumothorax":       8,
[0m[49m[39m  258, 270[0m:[39m[49m     "large_effusion":     6,
[0m[49m[39m  259, 271[0m:[39m[49m     "pulmonary_edema":    6,
[0m[49m[39m  260, 272[0m:[39m[49m     "mass_or_nodule":     4,
[0m[49m[39m  261, 273[0m:[39m[49m     "cardiomegaly":       2
[0m[49m[39m  262, 274[0m:[39m[49m }
[0m[49m[39m  263, 275[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  264, 276[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION calculate_priority(predictions):
[0m[49m[39m  265, 277[0m:[39m[49m     triggered_findings = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  266, 278[0m:[39m[49m     composite_score    = 0
[0m[49m[39m  267, 279[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  268, 280[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each finding, probability in predictions:
[0m[49m[39m  269, 281[0m:[39m[49m         IF finding in FINDING_THRESHOLDS:
[0m[49m[39m  270, 282[0m:[39m[49m             IF probability >= FINDING_THRESHOLDS[finding]:
[0m[49m[39m  271, 283[0m:[39m[49m                 // This finding exceeds its threshold. Flag it.
[0m[49m[39m  272, 284[0m:[39m[49m                 append to triggered_findings: {
[0m[49m[39m  273, 285[0m:[39m[49m                     finding:     finding,
[0m[49m[39m  274, 286[0m:[39m[49m                     probability: probability,
[0m[49m[39m  275, 287[0m:[39m[49m                     severity:    SEVERITY_WEIGHTS[finding]
[0m[49m[39m  276, 288[0m:[39m[49m                 }
[0m[49m[39m  277, 289[0m:[39m[49m                 // Add weighted contribution to composite score.
[0m[49m[39m  278, 290[0m:[39m[49m                 composite_score += probability * SEVERITY_WEIGHTS[finding]
[0m[49m[39m  279, 291[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  280, 292[0m:[39m[49m     // Determine priority level based on composite score and finding types.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Note: the severity-based rule takes precedence over composite score.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // A CRITICAL study may have a lower composite_score than an URGENT study
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // because the severity >= 8 rule fires first. For dashboard sorting,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // use priority level as primary sort and composite_score as secondary.
[0m[49m[39m  281, 297[0m:[39m[49m     IF any triggered finding has severity >= 8:
[0m[49m[39m  282, 298[0m:[39m[49m         priority = "CRITICAL"       // pneumothorax or tension: interrupt radiologist
[0m[49m[39m  283, 299[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE IF composite_score >= 5:
[0m[49m[39m  284, 300[0m:[39m[49m         priority = "URGENT"         // significant findings: move to top of queue
[0m[49m[39m  285, 301[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE IF length(triggered_findings) > 0:
[0m[49m[39m  286, 302[0m:[39m[49m         priority = "ELEVATED"       // minor findings flagged: slight priority boost
[0m[49m[39m  287, 303[0m:[39m[49m     ELSE:
[0m[49m[39m  288, 304[0m:[39m[49m         priority = "ROUTINE"        // no findings above threshold: normal queue order
[0m[49m[39m  289, 305[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  290, 306[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN {
[0m[49m[39m  291, 307[0m:[39m[49m         priority:           priority,
[0m[49m[39m  292, 308[0m:[39m[49m         composite_score:    composite_score,
[0m[49m[39m  293, 309[0m:[39m[49m         triggered_findings: triggered_findings
[0m[49m[39m  294, 310[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  295, 311[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  296, 312[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  297, 313[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Store results and update the worklist.** The final step persists the triage result for audit purposes and communicates the priority back to the PACS/RIS system to reorder the radiologist's worklist. The worklist update is the integration challenge. Every PACS vendor handles this differently. Common approaches include: sending an HL7 ORM message with updated priority, modifying the DICOM Modality Worklist entry, or using the PACS vendor's proprietary API. The audit record must capture everything: what was analyzed, what the model predicted, what priority was assigned, and when. This supports both HIPAA compliance and FDA post-market surveillance.
[0m[49m[39m  298, 314[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S2 (MEDIUM). The patient_id field is stored in the audit record. Add a justification comment explaining why (e.g., required for FDA post-market surveillance: must correlate AI findings with patient outcomes). If not needed for triage function itself, note that the DynamoDB table containing patient_id requires the same access controls as any PHI-containing data store. Alternatively, remove patient_id and note that patient linkage should be performed via PACS lookup using accession_number when needed. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  299, 317[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  300, 318[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION store_and_notify(study_id, accession_number, patient_id, priority_result):
[0m[49m[39m  301, 319[0m:[39m[49m     // Write the complete triage result to the audit database.
[0m[49m[39m  302, 320[0m:[39m[49m     write record to database table "triage-results":
[0m[49m[39m  303, 321[0m:[39m[49m         study_id          = study_id
[0m[49m[39m  304, 322[0m:[39m[49m         accession_number  = accession_number
[0m[49m[39m  305, 323[0m:[39m[49m         patient_id        = patient_id           // for linking back to clinical context
[0m[49m[39m  306, 324[0m:[39m[49m         model_version     = "cxr-triage-v2.1"   // track which model version produced this result
[0m[49m[39m  307, 325[0m:[39m[49m         inference_time    = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[39m  308, 326[0m:[39m[49m         priority          = priority_result.priority
[0m[49m[39m  309, 327[0m:[39m[49m         composite_score   = priority_result.composite_score
[0m[49m[39m  310, 328[0m:[39m[49m         findings          = priority_result.triggered_findings
[0m[49m[39m  311, 329[0m:[39m[49m         raw_predictions   = predictions          // full probability vector for audit
[0m[49m[39m  312, 330[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  313, 331[0m:[39m[49m     // If priority is CRITICAL or URGENT, update the radiologist worklist.
[0m[49m[39m  314, 332[0m:[39m[49m     IF priority_result.priority in ["CRITICAL", "URGENT"]:
[0m[49m[39m  315, 333[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  316, 334[0m:[39m[49m         // Send priority update to PACS/RIS via HL7 or vendor API.
[0m[49m[39m  317, 335[0m:[39m[49m         // The exact mechanism depends on your PACS vendor.
[0m[49m[39m  318, 336[0m:[39m[49m         send_worklist_update(
[0m[49m[39m  319, 337[0m:[39m[49m             accession_number = accession_number,
[0m[49m[39m  320, 338[0m:[39m[49m             new_priority     = priority_result.priority,
[0m[49m[39m  321, 339[0m:[39m[49m             reason           = format_finding_summary(priority_result.triggered_findings)
[0m[49m[39m  322, 340[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  323, 341[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  324, 342[0m:[39m[49m         // For CRITICAL findings, also send an immediate notification.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // The alert channel must be a HIPAA-compliant notification pathway.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // If using SNS, ensure all subscribers are covered under your BAA.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Send only accession number and priority level in the alert;
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // finding details should be accessible only through the authenticated
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // PACS/RIS interface to minimize PHI exposure.
[0m[49m[39m  325, 348[0m:[39m[49m         IF priority_result.priority == "CRITICAL":
[0m[49m[39m  326, 349[0m:[39m[49m             send_alert(
[0m[49m[39m  327, 350[0m:[39m[49m                 channel  = "radiology-urgent",
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 328     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m                 message  = "CRITICAL finding detected on study " + accession_number
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 329     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m                          + ": " + format_finding_summary(priority_result.triggered_findings)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 message  = "CRITICAL: Study " + accession_number
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                          + " requires immediate read"
[0m[49m[39m  330, 353[0m:[39m[49m             )
[0m[49m[39m  331, 354[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  332, 355[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  333, 356[0m:[39m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter09.05-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
